00:16:29.654 --> 00:16:31.174
I'd like to introduce our next speaker,

292
00:16:32.114 --> 00:16:35.724
Pegah Safabakhsh, who will be talking about tissue-based

293
00:16:35.794 --> 00:16:39.734
homologous recombination deficiency status prediction in

294
00:16:39.794 --> 00:16:42.774
patients with breast, ovarian, and pancreatic cancers.

295
00:16:45.014 --> 00:16:46.674
Hi, everyone. Thank you for the opportunity here.

296
00:16:47.974 --> 00:16:50.754
As mentioned, we're going to be talking about a genomic instability status

297
00:16:50.794 --> 00:16:54.634
prediction method in a tissue-based platform for breast,

298
00:16:54.674 --> 00:16:55.934
ovarian, and pancreatic cancer.

299
00:16:57.354 --> 00:16:59.454
These are my relevant financial disclosures.

300
00:17:00.674 --> 00:17:04.535
So just a bit of background on HRD, or homologous recombination

301
00:17:04.614 --> 00:17:06.994
deficiency. This is a molecular phenotype that's

302
00:17:07.035 --> 00:17:09.704
characterized by the inability to

303
00:17:10.594 --> 00:17:12.555
repair DNA double-stranded stranded breaks.

304
00:17:13.894 --> 00:17:17.734
Identifying these HRD tumors could help select patients that

305
00:17:17.954 --> 00:17:21.535
can benefit from DNA damage repair targeting therapies such as PARP

306
00:17:21.555 --> 00:17:23.874
inhibitors, and this is through synthetic lethality.

307
00:17:25.714 --> 00:17:29.694
HRD can lead to genomic instability, so this is detectable

308
00:17:29.814 --> 00:17:33.774
by targeted sequencing, and this can theoretically help identify

309
00:17:33.934 --> 00:17:37.754
a larger group of patients that might benefit from this therapy beyond just looking

310
00:17:37.834 --> 00:17:40.514
at BRCA1 and 2 or HRR gene mutations.

311
00:17:43.234 --> 00:17:47.004
So the method that we've developed is based on using the Guardant

312
00:17:47.134 --> 00:17:50.914
360 tissue platform. So this is a targeted next-gen sequencing assay.

313
00:17:51.754 --> 00:17:54.954
This profiles 741 cancer-associated genes.

314
00:17:55.494 --> 00:17:59.154
We do a full genomic profiling, including SNVs, indels, copy number

315
00:17:59.194 --> 00:18:03.024
alterations, fusions. There's also methylation profiling and

316
00:18:03.054 --> 00:18:04.314
whole transcriptome sequencing.

317
00:18:04.894 --> 00:18:08.094
So all of these would be profiled along with GIS or HRD.

318
00:18:09.454 --> 00:18:12.014
And this is the schema of the model that we've developed.

319
00:18:12.234 --> 00:18:15.914
So, a given sample is profiled on Guardant 360 tissue.

320
00:18:16.374 --> 00:18:20.244
We run it through a bioinformatics pipeline that does all the genomic variant

321
00:18:20.334 --> 00:18:23.954
calling, and we determine if the sample has a sufficient number

322
00:18:24.074 --> 00:18:27.774
of SNVs to basically apply

323
00:18:27.874 --> 00:18:30.534
a SNV signature prediction to it.

324
00:18:31.374 --> 00:18:35.274
If there are insufficient SNVs detected in the sample, then we

325
00:18:35.294 --> 00:18:39.274
employ the model on the bottom. So it's either including a CNV-based

326
00:18:39.674 --> 00:18:43.514
signature model or a model that includes both SBS or single-base

327
00:18:43.554 --> 00:18:47.054
substitution, along with copy number-based signatures.

328
00:18:47.574 --> 00:18:51.174
So together, these make an ensemble model.That produces a

329
00:18:51.254 --> 00:18:55.154
probabilistic score of being HRD, to which we apply a

330
00:18:55.214 --> 00:18:58.194
threshold that gives us a binary genomic instability status.

331
00:19:00.054 --> 00:19:03.524
The model was trained and validated using breast, ovarian, and pancreatic clinical

332
00:19:03.614 --> 00:19:05.614
samples that were tested on Guardant360 tissue.

333
00:19:06.194 --> 00:19:09.914
We used genomic labels based on biallelic loss in

334
00:19:09.934 --> 00:19:12.054
BRCA1 and 2 being HRD positive.

335
00:19:13.294 --> 00:19:17.194
And HRD negative or HRD proficient would be HRR wild type.

336
00:19:17.274 --> 00:19:20.734
So the absence of any genomic alterations in

337
00:19:20.774 --> 00:19:24.334
a larger list of 14 HRR genes that are listed at the bottom,

338
00:19:25.414 --> 00:19:27.954
as well as promoter methylation, which would also be excluded.

339
00:19:28.834 --> 00:19:29.174
And

340
00:19:30.294 --> 00:19:33.554
we use these as orthogonal HRD labels.

341
00:19:33.984 --> 00:19:37.794
So in summary, the GIS on Guardant360 tissue or genomic instability

342
00:19:37.834 --> 00:19:41.344
status is a probabilistic HRD prediction approach that we've developed

343
00:19:41.434 --> 00:19:45.194
using a combination of CNV and SNV-based biomarkers.

344
00:19:47.854 --> 00:19:50.894
So to dive a bit deeper into the SNV signature component,

345
00:19:51.714 --> 00:19:53.574
we looked at a

346
00:19:54.434 --> 00:19:58.404
set of published signatures from COSMIC that we selected

347
00:19:58.454 --> 00:20:00.894
a subset of for inclusion in the model.

348
00:20:01.074 --> 00:20:05.034
So we basically looked at each sample's SNVs that

349
00:20:05.074 --> 00:20:08.834
were detected and can develop a projection score

350
00:20:08.894 --> 00:20:10.854
using the SBS signatures from COSMIC.

351
00:20:11.334 --> 00:20:15.024
And then we looked at the differences between our HRD negative and

352
00:20:15.094 --> 00:20:18.754
positive labels to identify signatures that were statistically different

353
00:20:18.774 --> 00:20:22.744
between those two groups. And so on the right, we're showing

354
00:20:23.154 --> 00:20:27.024
the box plot of the scores that we derived from our training samples.

355
00:20:27.634 --> 00:20:28.744
And we see that

356
00:20:30.254 --> 00:20:34.014
the first two signatures identified on the left are commonly

357
00:20:34.054 --> 00:20:37.044
associated with HRD, SBS3 and SBS39.

358
00:20:37.834 --> 00:20:41.814
And just also want to remind that this is a targeted panel, so these

359
00:20:41.834 --> 00:20:44.374
were typically derived from whole genome sequencing.

360
00:20:44.434 --> 00:20:47.614
And so the fact that we were able to detect these signatures

361
00:20:49.014 --> 00:20:52.554
was a great thing to see. And we also

362
00:20:52.574 --> 00:20:56.514
detected two other signatures that were associated with deficient mismatch

363
00:20:56.554 --> 00:20:58.653
repair, so SBS6 and SBS15.

364
00:21:00.493 --> 00:21:04.414
The SBS3 and SBS39 were increased in BRCA biallelic samples

365
00:21:04.474 --> 00:21:08.314
as compared to HR wild type, and mismatch repair

366
00:21:08.374 --> 00:21:11.054
deficiency signatures were decreased in BRCA biallelic samples.

367
00:21:11.094 --> 00:21:14.994
So this is consistent with the idea that dmmr and

368
00:21:15.114 --> 00:21:17.084
HRD are generally mutually exclusive.

369
00:21:17.994 --> 00:21:21.754
We also detected SBS5, which is a clock-like signature, but

370
00:21:22.254 --> 00:21:25.914
the decrease in BRCA biallelic was also seen, but it was to a much lesser extent

371
00:21:25.954 --> 00:21:27.813
than we saw in dmmr.

372
00:21:31.854 --> 00:21:35.634
So in terms of the overall model accuracy, we were able to

373
00:21:35.644 --> 00:21:38.404
achieve an AUC of 0.98 in a test cohort of

374
00:21:38.454 --> 00:21:42.354
164 Guardant360 clinical samples, and

375
00:21:42.414 --> 00:21:43.794
the ROC curve on the right is shown.

376
00:21:44.834 --> 00:21:48.644
For sensitivity assessment, we looked at the positive detection rate in

377
00:21:48.694 --> 00:21:51.614
BRCA1 and 2 biallelic loss samples in the same test cohort.

378
00:21:52.114 --> 00:21:55.934
We also looked at a smaller independent AV cohort of 31 samples.

379
00:21:56.814 --> 00:21:58.294
The results are shown at the bottom.

380
00:21:59.294 --> 00:22:02.984
We were able to achieve 88% to 96% sensitivity in ovarian,

381
00:22:03.714 --> 00:22:07.063
78% to 96% in breast, and 80% in pancreatic.

382
00:22:09.554 --> 00:22:13.074
For specificity, we estimated this looking at the HR wild type group.

383
00:22:13.174 --> 00:22:16.754
So we looked at negative percent agreement or NPA, and we had

384
00:22:17.054 --> 00:22:20.714
100% across most of the cohorts, with one pancreatic cohort

385
00:22:21.214 --> 00:22:22.424
coming in at 93%.

386
00:22:23.294 --> 00:22:26.914
You'll notice that we included one cohort that were non-HRD,

387
00:22:27.074 --> 00:22:30.874
typically HRD cancer types, colorectal, esophageal, gastric,

388
00:22:30.934 --> 00:22:34.774
bladder, and bile duct. This was to supplement the cohort given the

389
00:22:34.994 --> 00:22:38.924
relatively low prevalence of HR wild type samples amongst ovarian, breast, and

390
00:22:38.954 --> 00:22:42.554
pancreatic. And in that cohort, we also observed 100%

391
00:22:42.594 --> 00:22:43.174
specificity.

392
00:22:46.514 --> 00:22:50.464
So to look at the landscape of GIS, we looked

393
00:22:50.494 --> 00:22:53.884
at a cohort of clinical Guardant360 tissue samples,

394
00:22:54.554 --> 00:22:56.974
and we first looked at the overall prevalence.

395
00:22:57.094 --> 00:23:00.954
So we found that we were able to detect GIS in about a third of

396
00:23:01.014 --> 00:23:04.714
breast samples, 45% of ovarian samples, and about

397
00:23:04.754 --> 00:23:06.374
14% of pancreatic samples.

398
00:23:07.514 --> 00:23:11.054
So we've broken those down by patients that have GIS

399
00:23:11.074 --> 00:23:14.894
detected, as well as BRCA1 and 2 pathogenic mutations.

400
00:23:15.394 --> 00:23:19.114
And then the middle blue color identifies the patients that would not

401
00:23:19.154 --> 00:23:20.294
typically be

402
00:23:21.434 --> 00:23:24.114
recommended for DDR targeting therapies that have

403
00:23:24.834 --> 00:23:27.614
HRR alterations but are not necessarily pathogenic.

404
00:23:28.994 --> 00:23:30.574
And so we

405
00:23:31.454 --> 00:23:34.594
observed that about half the cases across the cancer types

406
00:23:35.574 --> 00:23:36.064
were

407
00:23:37.294 --> 00:23:39.534
overlapping with BRCA1 and 2 pathogenic mutations.

408
00:23:40.474 --> 00:23:44.374
And so this middle blue color represents this expanded patient

409
00:23:44.434 --> 00:23:46.214
population for therapy selection.

410
00:23:47.594 --> 00:23:50.994
These are the patients that do not have BRCA1 and 2 pathogenic

411
00:23:51.054 --> 00:23:51.614
mutations.

412
00:23:52.694 --> 00:23:55.244
Within that group, we also looked at

413
00:23:55.914 --> 00:23:59.134
more clear potential drivers that could be driving

414
00:23:59.154 --> 00:24:02.954
GIS in terms of pathogenic mutations in non-BRCA1 and

415
00:24:03.114 --> 00:24:06.834
2. But we found that only about 2% to 3% of ovarian and breast

416
00:24:07.074 --> 00:24:09.054
patients could be attributed to that genotype.

417
00:24:09.134 --> 00:24:09.254
So

418
00:24:10.134 --> 00:24:13.314
we still think that there's a benefit to using GIS to

419
00:24:13.374 --> 00:24:17.034
identify these patients that would not have been captured by

420
00:24:17.614 --> 00:24:19.134
deleterious HRR mutations.

421
00:24:22.094 --> 00:24:25.834
So to wrap up, here today we showed a genomic instability

422
00:24:25.934 --> 00:24:28.554
status method, GIS, on Guardant360 tissue.

423
00:24:29.034 --> 00:24:32.654
This was a probabilistic model that we developed on SNV and CNV-based

424
00:24:32.674 --> 00:24:36.374
signatures to predict HRD status in breast, pancreatic, and ovarian cancer with

425
00:24:36.414 --> 00:24:37.194
high accuracy.

426
00:24:38.954 --> 00:24:42.614
This displays the utility for potentially broadening the identification of

427
00:24:42.634 --> 00:24:46.014
patients who might benefit from DDR-targeting therapies beyond

428
00:24:46.034 --> 00:24:48.004
conventional HRG mutation

429
00:24:48.054 --> 00:24:51.838
testing.We also wanted to highlight

430
00:24:51.848 --> 00:24:55.578
that we have GIS available in Guardant360 Liquid.

431
00:24:55.958 --> 00:24:59.828
And so patients that in our profile with both liquid and tissue assays on

432
00:24:59.858 --> 00:25:03.738
Guardant360 can now be comprehensively monitored for HRD

433
00:25:03.998 --> 00:25:06.378
using a combination of these two assays.

434
00:25:08.598 --> 00:25:09.718
For some of our future work,

435
00:25:10.538 --> 00:25:14.198
we recognize that prostate cancer also has a great ability

436
00:25:14.318 --> 00:25:18.258
to-- GIS can have a great ability to expand patient selection

437
00:25:18.278 --> 00:25:19.098
for prostate cancer.

438
00:25:20.758 --> 00:25:22.378
In our initial development work, we've

439
00:25:23.398 --> 00:25:26.848
observed a distinct genomic scarring signature in prostate, suggesting

440
00:25:26.878 --> 00:25:30.558
that a cancer-specific model will be needed, and we're currently

441
00:25:30.578 --> 00:25:31.898
developing that. It's in progress.

442
00:25:33.738 --> 00:25:36.958
And of course, we want to clinically validate this as a predictive

443
00:25:37.018 --> 00:25:40.588
biomarker in patients that are treated with DDR targeting

444
00:25:40.658 --> 00:25:42.118
therapies such as PARP inhibitors.

445
00:25:43.238 --> 00:25:44.798
And that's all I have. Thank you.

446
00:25:53.218 --> 00:25:55.618
At this point, we'd like to open it up to the audience for questions.

447
00:26:00.678 --> 00:26:04.418
I have one for you. Your model identifies

448
00:26:04.538 --> 00:26:08.338
many HRD positive tumors, and they extend beyond

449
00:26:08.398 --> 00:26:10.218
just BRCA mutations.

450
00:26:11.278 --> 00:26:12.968
When we think about PARP selection,

451
00:26:14.098 --> 00:26:18.058
how do you envision this sort of playing out in clinical practice and in clinical

452
00:26:18.098 --> 00:26:18.778
trial design?

453
00:26:20.678 --> 00:26:24.418
Yeah. So we envision a BRCA or

454
00:26:24.478 --> 00:26:25.488
GIS type model,

455
00:26:26.498 --> 00:26:30.098
which has been employed by Myriad, which was approved for ovarian

456
00:26:30.558 --> 00:26:34.518
cancer in the past. I think we see that BRCA is an

