757
00:44:19.642 --> 00:44:20.922
that a polyp that was seen

758
00:44:21.742 --> 00:44:25.182
and removed during index colonoscopy can undergo recurrence,

759
00:44:25.682 --> 00:44:29.501
but at some point it can also finally transform to cancer, making it the

760
00:44:29.522 --> 00:44:32.942
POP-CRC or the cancerous outcome.

761
00:44:33.362 --> 00:44:37.262
The goal of studying these polyp outcome phenotypes

762
00:44:37.322 --> 00:44:40.802
is to provide precision prediction, which is to identify molecular

763
00:44:40.882 --> 00:44:44.762
differences between polyps at the very first time that these

764
00:44:44.842 --> 00:44:48.722
polyps were removed during index colonoscopy, despite

765
00:44:48.782 --> 00:44:50.642
sharing similar morphological features.

766
00:44:51.442 --> 00:44:54.992
To further understand precision prediction, I will be walking us through five sets

767
00:44:55.022 --> 00:44:55.842
of results today.

768
00:44:56.682 --> 00:45:00.482
The first one is comparing the polyp that progressed to cancer to the polyp

769
00:45:00.492 --> 00:45:04.142
that did not recur to understand signs of progression.

770
00:45:04.222 --> 00:45:08.182
The second is comparing the polyp that progressed to cancer to the recurring

771
00:45:08.302 --> 00:45:10.532
polyp that did not progress to cancer.

772
00:45:11.502 --> 00:45:15.382
The third is comparing the cancer-free outcomes, the recurring polyp to the

773
00:45:15.402 --> 00:45:18.862
non-recurring polyp, to understand signs of recurrence.

774
00:45:19.722 --> 00:45:22.902
The fourth is actually looking at the mutually shared

775
00:45:22.942 --> 00:45:26.882
features between the polyp that progressed to cancer and the polyp that

776
00:45:27.002 --> 00:45:30.922
recurred but did not progress to cancer to look for signs of abnormality in

777
00:45:30.962 --> 00:45:33.682
the first polyp tissue that was removed during index colonoscopy.

778
00:45:34.462 --> 00:45:38.422
And finally, the fifth one is uniquely looking at the features

779
00:45:38.502 --> 00:45:42.342
in the polyp that turned to cancer compared to both the

780
00:45:42.402 --> 00:45:43.422
cancer-free outcomes.

781
00:45:44.542 --> 00:45:48.522
The method we are using to study precision prediction, one of the methods

782
00:45:48.982 --> 00:45:51.742
is spatial transcriptomics using nanoString geomics.

783
00:45:52.462 --> 00:45:56.402
We have profiled roughly between six to 12 donors for each of

784
00:45:56.442 --> 00:46:00.142
the polyp outcome phenotypes. And for each of the donors, we are

785
00:46:00.162 --> 00:46:03.222
profiling multiple regions from the first polyp.

786
00:46:03.882 --> 00:46:07.582
Further, those regions are spatially resolved using the PanCK

787
00:46:08.162 --> 00:46:12.122
stain. So PanCK positive are the green regions, which mark the

788
00:46:12.162 --> 00:46:16.062
epithelial cells. And PanCK negative are the surrounding red

789
00:46:16.142 --> 00:46:20.072
region, which marks the stroma or the tumor, or

790
00:46:20.142 --> 00:46:23.602
the microenvironment around these epithelial cells that include

791
00:46:23.662 --> 00:46:27.262
fibroblasts, endothelial cells, immune cells, and macrophages.

792
00:46:28.302 --> 00:46:31.962
Diving into the first result that is comparing the polyp that progressed to cancer

793
00:46:32.002 --> 00:46:35.882
to the polyp that did not recur, we see a reduction of

794
00:46:35.902 --> 00:46:39.522
expression in the immune defense gene and also in the

795
00:46:39.582 --> 00:46:43.502
MUC2 gene, which is responsible for intestinal barrier function

796
00:46:43.542 --> 00:46:46.442
in the epithelial and the stromal compartments.

797
00:46:46.482 --> 00:46:50.182
When we are looking at the cell type abundances, each dot here represents

798
00:46:50.222 --> 00:46:52.902
multiple regions from multiple patients.

799
00:46:53.902 --> 00:46:57.762
When we are looking at the differences in the cell type abundances, we see that the

800
00:46:57.842 --> 00:47:01.482
polyp that progressed to cancer shows poor mucosal immune

801
00:47:01.522 --> 00:47:05.042
protection due to reduction of the IgA plasma cells, IgM

802
00:47:05.122 --> 00:47:08.842
plasma and macrophages, and also due to the reduction in the chemokine

803
00:47:08.882 --> 00:47:09.742
signaling pathway.

804
00:47:10.882 --> 00:47:14.302
Along with this, we also see a gain of stem cell-like properties

805
00:47:14.862 --> 00:47:18.662
marked by the increase in the TUFT cells and the cells expressing claudin-10

806
00:47:18.682 --> 00:47:22.182
plus, along with a decrease in the apoptotic signal.

807
00:47:22.242 --> 00:47:26.152
In the stromal compartment, in the polyp that progressed to

808
00:47:26.182 --> 00:47:29.922
cancer, we see reduced mucosal antigen surveillance and

809
00:47:29.962 --> 00:47:33.322
compromised intestinal barrier marked by the reduction of

810
00:47:34.422 --> 00:47:38.122
microfold cell proportion, along with reduced differentiation

811
00:47:38.202 --> 00:47:39.802
marked by the PPAR signaling.

812
00:47:41.082 --> 00:47:44.982
From the second result, when we are comparing the polyp that progressed to cancer

813
00:47:45.021 --> 00:47:48.862
to the recurring polyp, but it did not progress to cancer, we

814
00:47:48.922 --> 00:47:52.752
again see a reduction of expression of these immune defense genes,

815
00:47:53.302 --> 00:47:56.922
along with a reduced expression of epithelial differentiation marked by

816
00:47:56.942 --> 00:48:00.042
PHGR1 and downregulation of

817
00:48:00.082 --> 00:48:03.342
FAP1 that is responsible for enterocyte and colonocyte

818
00:48:03.382 --> 00:48:04.182
differentiation.

819
00:48:05.082 --> 00:48:08.732
When we are looking at the pathways, we see a loss of metabolically

820
00:48:08.842 --> 00:48:12.422
active immune compartment and differentiated epithelial compartments

821
00:48:12.882 --> 00:48:16.562
marked by a reduced signal of glycolysis and oxidative phosphorylation

822
00:48:17.082 --> 00:48:20.942
in the polyp that progressed to cancer, and also reduced breakdown

823
00:48:21.042 --> 00:48:24.822
of the branched-chain amino acids, which is linked to development and progression

824
00:48:24.862 --> 00:48:28.842
of polyps. In the stromal compartment, we see reduction of the base

825
00:48:28.882 --> 00:48:32.762
accession repair, pointing to more oxidative damage and

826
00:48:32.802 --> 00:48:36.632
mutation accumulation, and reduced homologous recombination,

827
00:48:36.802 --> 00:48:40.722
pointing to the polyp that progressed to cancer being repair impaired

828
00:48:40.732 --> 00:48:41.962
and genomically unstable.

829
00:48:43.062 --> 00:48:47.002
In the third result, where we are comparing the cancer-free outcomes, the

830
00:48:47.042 --> 00:48:50.202
recurring to the non-recurring polyp, we see again a

831
00:48:50.302 --> 00:48:53.742
downregulation of the immune genes, along with loss of

832
00:48:53.802 --> 00:48:57.462
intestinal protective barrier program marked by downregulation of

833
00:48:57.482 --> 00:49:01.142
MUC2 and poor differentiation marked by downregulation of

834
00:49:01.182 --> 00:49:01.982
KRT20.

835
00:49:02.962 --> 00:49:06.922
When we are looking at the differences in the cell type abundances, we see reduced

836
00:49:06.982 --> 00:49:10.722
mucosal barrier protection marked by the reduction of IgA

837
00:49:10.742 --> 00:49:14.562
plasma cells and macrophages, along with more stem cell-like

838
00:49:14.602 --> 00:49:18.482
and proliferative states, again marked by the transit-amplifying cells, the

839
00:49:18.502 --> 00:49:22.382
stem cells, TUFT cells, and reduced apoptotic

840
00:49:22.442 --> 00:49:26.262
signal. In the stroma, we see that the polyp

841
00:49:26.302 --> 00:49:29.522
that recurred showed compromised intestinal barrier

842
00:49:29.942 --> 00:49:33.662
protection due to reduction of the microfold cells abundance and

843
00:49:33.822 --> 00:49:37.622
also altered metabolism and differentiation function due to

844
00:49:37.662 --> 00:49:41.544
reduction of the PPAR signaling.When we are looking

845
00:49:41.714 --> 00:49:45.694
at the features that were shared mutually by the polyps that

846
00:49:45.714 --> 00:49:49.474
recurred but did not progress to cancer and the polyp that recurred but did

847
00:49:49.494 --> 00:49:51.694
progress to cancer, we again see

848
00:49:53.154 --> 00:49:56.614
poor mucosal immune protection marked by reduction of

849
00:49:56.674 --> 00:50:00.454
IgLL5, downregulation of IgHM, and fewer IgA

850
00:50:00.514 --> 00:50:04.414
plasma cells and macrophages. And in the stroma, we see increased

851
00:50:04.454 --> 00:50:08.404
expression of MCT2B, which is an oncogenic driver in

852
00:50:08.454 --> 00:50:09.474
non-small cell

853
00:50:10.634 --> 00:50:11.434
lung carcinoma.

854
00:50:12.834 --> 00:50:16.484
Reduced expression of KRT20, marking poor differentiation,

855
00:50:17.174 --> 00:50:21.134
reduced expression of MUC2 gene marking reduced colon protective barrier,

856
00:50:21.714 --> 00:50:25.614
and reduced mucosal antigen surveillance by fewer

857
00:50:25.694 --> 00:50:29.534
microfold cells. Finally, when we are looking at the features that were

858
00:50:29.614 --> 00:50:33.534
uniquely seen in the polyp that progressed to cancer, comparing to both

859
00:50:33.594 --> 00:50:37.554
of the cancer-free outcomes, we again see reduced immune

860
00:50:37.614 --> 00:50:41.134
surveillance and reduced epithelial

861
00:50:41.194 --> 00:50:45.074
differentiation marked by PHGR1, reduced enterocyte and colonocyte

862
00:50:45.134 --> 00:50:48.814
differentiation marked by FAP1, and reduced branching acid

863
00:50:48.994 --> 00:50:52.254
breakdown. In the stromal compartment, again, we see

864
00:50:52.794 --> 00:50:56.194
reduced IgLL5 pointing to lower

865
00:50:56.334 --> 00:51:00.074
antibody and plasma producing capacity, along with a weaker

866
00:51:00.154 --> 00:51:04.014
capacity to transport those antibodies into the lumen, and

867
00:51:04.094 --> 00:51:06.773
altered metabolism marked by oxidative phosphorylation.

868
00:51:08.034 --> 00:51:11.994
To summarize, I want to reiterate that we see these observations in the

869
00:51:12.034 --> 00:51:15.914
very first polyp tissue that was resected during index colonoscopy.

870
00:51:16.634 --> 00:51:20.454
In the non-recurring polyp, we see intact epithelium and balanced

871
00:51:20.494 --> 00:51:24.254
stroma. In the polyp that recurred but did not progress to cancer,

872
00:51:24.754 --> 00:51:28.434
we see reduced barrier protection, reduced immune surveillance,

873
00:51:28.654 --> 00:51:31.394
and mild proliferation along with epithelial plasticity.

874
00:51:32.134 --> 00:51:34.314
And in the polyp that progressed to cancer,

875
00:51:35.794 --> 00:51:39.214
we see a higher immune defense loss, lower

876
00:51:39.254 --> 00:51:42.714
differentiation, more stemness and proliferative state,

877
00:51:43.034 --> 00:51:46.994
along with an altered stroma. And this was in the polyp that was removed

878
00:51:47.034 --> 00:51:48.134
at the very first time,

879
00:51:49.094 --> 00:51:51.484
many months or many years before it turned to cancer.

880
00:51:52.334 --> 00:51:56.223
This gives a model of spatially resolved markers and

881
00:51:56.254 --> 00:51:59.734
mechanisms that can be studied from the index colonoscopy,

882
00:52:00.234 --> 00:52:03.554
which could help stratify patients for better surveillance

883
00:52:03.634 --> 00:52:07.474
intervals to address recurrence and to identify

884
00:52:07.494 --> 00:52:09.894
targets for preventing its progression to cancer.

885
00:52:11.074 --> 00:52:13.994
I want to acknowledge Dr. Boardman for

886
00:52:14.934 --> 00:52:18.574
giving me this opportunity and her excellent mentorship, and all members of the

887
00:52:18.594 --> 00:52:22.334
Boardman lab, our collaborators, and our funding sources as well.

888
00:52:22.394 --> 00:52:22.714
Thank you.

889
00:52:31.334 --> 00:52:33.934
Thank you very much. I have a question.

890
00:52:33.994 --> 00:52:35.234
So you've seen

891
00:52:36.194 --> 00:52:40.033
very interesting patterns of the different markers in the

892
00:52:40.104 --> 00:52:41.714
polyps that progress and the

893
00:52:42.714 --> 00:52:44.664
ones that don't or they recur or they progress.

894
00:52:45.304 --> 00:52:48.783
So what do you think are the next steps to combine this

895
00:52:48.814 --> 00:52:52.734
information and convert it into a combined biomarker that will

896
00:52:53.074 --> 00:52:56.814
give you a probability of progression so that then can be used in the clinic?

897
00:52:56.874 --> 00:53:00.354
So if you can comment a little bit more how we use that information

898
00:53:00.414 --> 00:53:04.374
to have an actionable

899
00:53:04.934 --> 00:53:05.474
biomarker.

900
00:53:06.074 --> 00:53:07.714
Right. I think we are working on

901
00:53:08.574 --> 00:53:09.494
having a

902
00:53:10.354 --> 00:53:12.494
clinical panel that we can

903
00:53:13.874 --> 00:53:16.914
put into use, like for translational purposes.

904
00:53:17.394 --> 00:53:21.174
Recently, Dr. Boardman did receive the funding from Mayo Clinic

905
00:53:21.254 --> 00:53:24.274
Ventures, and we are currently working on

906
00:53:25.314 --> 00:53:28.854
extracting more tissues for these purposes

907
00:53:28.894 --> 00:53:31.754
exactly, and that is actually ongoing currently.

908
00:53:32.974 --> 00:53:35.334
Thank you.

909
00:53:40.294 --> 00:53:42.854
Okay. If there are no other questions, thank you-

910
00:53:43.094 --> 00:53:43.164
Thank you

911
00:53:43.174 --> 00:53:44.554
... for a wonderful presentation.

912
00:53:47.754 --> 00:53:48.694
Thank you.

913
00:53:48.794 --> 00:53:52.684
I'd now like to introduce Yong-Jun Cha, who will be talking about

914
00:53:52.684 --> 00:53:56.254
"Clinical Validation of Whole Exome Sequence-Based HRD

915
00:53:56.264 --> 00:54:00.214
Scoring and Its Prognostic Value for PARP Inhibitor

916
00:54:00.313 --> 00:54:01.834
Maintenance in Ovarian Cancer."

917
00:54:03.694 --> 00:54:06.474
Yeah. Thank you for your introduction, and

918
00:54:07.714 --> 00:54:11.454
good afternoon, everyone. I'm Yong-Jun Cha from IMBDx,

919
00:54:12.474 --> 00:54:16.074
and I'm very honored to speak here on behalf of our colleagues.

920
00:54:16.694 --> 00:54:20.354
And today, I will present our clinical validation study of whole

921
00:54:20.434 --> 00:54:24.044
exome sequencing based HR scoring and its positive

922
00:54:24.114 --> 00:54:27.594
value for PARP inhibitor maintenance therapy in ovarian cancer.

923
00:54:29.874 --> 00:54:30.954
Here are my disclosures.

924
00:54:32.094 --> 00:54:35.854
So homologous recombination deficiency, HRD, is an established

925
00:54:35.994 --> 00:54:39.854
biomarker response to PARP inhibitor maintenance

926
00:54:39.914 --> 00:54:43.644
in epithelial ovarian cancer. And currently, it guides the

927
00:54:43.654 --> 00:54:47.384
treatment selection for two PARP inhibitor regimen, olaparib

928
00:54:47.574 --> 00:54:50.894
plus bevacizumab or niraparib in the first-line maintenance

929
00:54:50.954 --> 00:54:51.754
setting.

930
00:54:52.834 --> 00:54:56.014
In the current practice, however, HRD is

931
00:54:56.534 --> 00:54:59.874
currently assessed mostly by a dedicated single-purpose

932
00:55:00.134 --> 00:55:00.594
assay,

933
00:55:01.514 --> 00:55:02.094
which is seen

934
00:55:03.394 --> 00:55:07.114
separately from comprehensive genome profiling or germline

935
00:55:08.474 --> 00:55:09.014
profiling.

936
00:55:10.094 --> 00:55:13.814
And that means that patient need multiple testing and more

937
00:55:13.994 --> 00:55:16.714
tissue and time and a longer workflow.

938
00:55:17.954 --> 00:55:21.774
So we reasoned that the integrated paired tumor

939
00:55:21.814 --> 00:55:25.094
normal whole exome sequencing would consolidate

940
00:55:26.774 --> 00:55:30.494
comprehensive genome profiling and germline testing and HRD

941
00:55:30.534 --> 00:55:34.214
assessment in single assay. And in this study,

942
00:55:34.594 --> 00:55:38.294
we evaluated the clinical validity of our whole exome sequencing

943
00:55:38.374 --> 00:55:42.334
based HRD scoring in an independent ovarian

944
00:55:42.394 --> 00:55:46.090
cancer cohort.So this is a single

945
00:55:46.150 --> 00:55:50.030
institution retrospective biomarker study at Seoul National University Hospital,

946
00:55:51.690 --> 00:55:55.670
consisting of 81 patients who either received

947
00:55:55.690 --> 00:55:59.610
the PARP inhibitor or bevacizumab as maintenance therapy

948
00:55:59.650 --> 00:56:02.450
in the first-line or second-line treatment.

949
00:56:02.930 --> 00:56:06.490
And we mainly examined the progression-free

950
00:56:06.570 --> 00:56:09.910
survival in the first-line and second-line maintenance

951
00:56:09.950 --> 00:56:10.670
therapy

952
00:56:11.910 --> 00:56:14.010
according to the HRD scoring.

953
00:56:14.950 --> 00:56:18.690
And as you can see, half of the patients received the upfront neoadjuvant

954
00:56:18.750 --> 00:56:22.590
chemotherapy followed by interval debulking surgery, and another half

955
00:56:22.650 --> 00:56:23.090
received

956
00:56:23.970 --> 00:56:25.690
primary debulking surgery upfront.

957
00:56:27.350 --> 00:56:31.270
And for each patient, we performed the tumor germline whole exome

958
00:56:31.310 --> 00:56:33.590
sequencing CGP, called the cancer profiler,

959
00:56:34.510 --> 00:56:37.230
on tumor FFPE and PBMC,

960
00:56:38.130 --> 00:56:41.890
and our HRD scoring with some LOH and TAI

961
00:56:42.110 --> 00:56:44.710
and LSD scores, and we defined

962
00:56:45.570 --> 00:56:49.209
those having more than 50 as HRD-High.

963
00:56:50.110 --> 00:56:53.610
And apart from HRD scoring, we also

964
00:56:53.910 --> 00:56:55.550
called the BRCA status

965
00:56:56.710 --> 00:56:59.970
as part of our whole exome sequencing based

966
00:57:00.250 --> 00:57:03.820
CGP, and BRCA mutation was defined as

967
00:57:04.050 --> 00:57:07.650
pathogenic germline with somatic mutation or large genomic rearrangement.

968
00:57:10.710 --> 00:57:14.530
And for further analysis, we also used the current

969
00:57:15.030 --> 00:57:16.650
HRD positive definition,

970
00:57:17.670 --> 00:57:21.630
which is either HRD-High or BRCA mutation.

971
00:57:23.530 --> 00:57:27.250
So a quick note on the HRD scoring. We used the modified

972
00:57:27.310 --> 00:57:31.150
scar HRD-based workflow in which the whole exome sequencing-derived tumor

973
00:57:31.190 --> 00:57:34.750
fraction was incorporated into upstream copy number inference,

974
00:57:35.430 --> 00:57:39.250
which improves the calling stability, especially at low tumor

975
00:57:39.270 --> 00:57:39.730
purity.

976
00:57:40.730 --> 00:57:43.880
And we used the HRD high cutoff of 50,

977
00:57:45.290 --> 00:57:48.850
because in our internal development cohort across

978
00:57:49.230 --> 00:57:52.810
cancers with multiple histology, including ovarian cancer

979
00:57:53.310 --> 00:57:57.270
and also treatment-naive breast cancer, cutoff of 50

980
00:57:58.210 --> 00:58:02.070
showed more robustly disconnected BRCA-associated phenotype

981
00:58:02.310 --> 00:58:05.150
and also aligned better with the clinical outcomes.

982
00:58:05.610 --> 00:58:06.310
And also is

983
00:58:07.350 --> 00:58:10.930
in line with another recent publication using

984
00:58:11.010 --> 00:58:14.730
a very similar whole exome sequencing-based HRD assay.

985
00:58:15.430 --> 00:58:16.170
In that study,

986
00:58:16.990 --> 00:58:20.950
HRD high cutoff of 50 actually corresponds to the clinical validity

987
00:58:20.990 --> 00:58:23.850
to my choice to the CDx cutoff of 42.

988
00:58:27.130 --> 00:58:30.570
So turning back to the patient population, the median age was

989
00:58:30.690 --> 00:58:34.490
56, and most patients had high-grade serous and Stage

990
00:58:34.770 --> 00:58:36.450
3 or 4 tumor.

991
00:58:37.470 --> 00:58:38.310
And for the

992
00:58:39.430 --> 00:58:43.110
main analysis set, there is a patient with

993
00:58:43.210 --> 00:58:45.670
first-line and second-line maintenance therapy.

994
00:58:46.230 --> 00:58:49.790
Most of patients, there is 87

995
00:58:49.850 --> 00:58:52.830
patients and 65 patients in the

996
00:58:54.210 --> 00:58:57.690
first and second line received a PARP inhibitor as maintenance therapy,

997
00:58:58.690 --> 00:59:01.490
and bevacizumab in the remaining population.

998
00:59:04.210 --> 00:59:07.710
A quick look at the overall genomic landscape.

999
00:59:08.170 --> 00:59:11.870
As you can see, TP53 was the dominant alteration, and most

1000
00:59:11.970 --> 00:59:15.930
patients nearly universally had the TP53 alteration, and

1001
00:59:15.990 --> 00:59:19.110
with recurrent events in BRCA and other

1002
00:59:19.530 --> 00:59:23.070
HR spectrum mutations.

1003
00:59:26.510 --> 00:59:30.050
And looking at distribution of whole exome

1004
00:59:30.090 --> 00:59:31.450
sequencing HRD score,

1005
00:59:32.730 --> 00:59:36.150
you can see the two-third of patients was defined as

1006
00:59:36.510 --> 00:59:40.500
HRD-High, and around half are

1007
00:59:40.530 --> 00:59:43.870
found to have a BRCA mutation. And as you can see,

